<!-- Slide 9.9: Where this is going — substantiated forward look -->
<div class="content-slide future">
  <p class="overline">Opinionated Forward Look</p>
  <h2>Where This Is <span class="highlight">Going</span></h2>
  <p class="lead future__lead">
    <strong>CodeAct</strong> gives agents a flexible action format: write code, run it,
    inspect results, repeat. The next frontier is the harness around that action:
    what steers it, what feeds it, and what bounds it.
  </p>

  <!-- Core rail + three harness layers: cleaner than the earlier orbital diagram. -->
  <div class="orbit" aria-label="CodeAct as the action format, with three harness layers around it">
    <div class="orbit__core" aria-label="CodeAct: the settled action format">
      <div class="core">
        <span class="core__tag">Settled action format</span>
        <span class="core__title">CodeAct</span>
        <span class="core__sub">write &rarr; run &rarr; inspect &rarr; repeat</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="orbit__bridge" aria-hidden="true"><span>Harness layers</span></div>

    <div class="layer layer--judgment">
      <div class="layer__head">
        <span class="layer__node" aria-hidden="true">01</span>
        <div class="layer__heading">
          <p class="layer__verb">Steers</p>
          <h3 class="layer__title">Judgment &amp; planning</h3>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="layer__body">
        <p class="layer__claim">Acting is easy; knowing <em>which</em> action advances the goal &mdash; decompose, route, continue, stop &mdash; lives above the model.</p>
        <div class="layer__chips" aria-label="Examples shown earlier">
          <span>OmO planners</span>
          <span>routing</span>
          <span>optimizer loop</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="layer layer--context">
      <div class="layer__head">
        <span class="layer__node" aria-hidden="true">02</span>
        <div class="layer__heading">
          <p class="layer__verb">Feeds</p>
          <h3 class="layer__title">Context economics</h3>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="layer__body">
        <p class="layer__claim">More code &rArr; more output flooding the window. The practical lesson: <em>context quality beats window size</em> &mdash; agents degrade from bloat, not token caps.</p>
        <div class="layer__chips" aria-label="Examples shown earlier">
          <span>RTK</span>
          <span>Headroom</span>
          <span>CodeGraph</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="layer layer--trust">
      <div class="layer__head">
        <span class="layer__node" aria-hidden="true">03</span>
        <div class="layer__heading">
          <p class="layer__verb">Bounds</p>
          <h3 class="layer__title">Trust &amp; verification</h3>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="layer__body">
        <p class="layer__claim">The more code an agent runs unattended, the higher the stakes. Sandboxing, gating, and scoring the agent <em>can&rsquo;t see the answers to</em> keep it usable.</p>
        <div class="layer__chips" aria-label="Examples shown earlier">
          <span>permissions</span>
          <span>gates</span>
          <span>fixed rubric</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="future__kicker">
    Control the harness: judgment, context, verification.
    <strong>Pick one workflow. Measure one loop. Iterate.</strong>
  </p>

  <p class="slide-cite">
    <span class="slide-cite__tag">Sources</span>
    CodeAct: Wang et al., <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.01030" target="_blank" rel="noopener">&ldquo;Executable Code Actions Elicit Better LLM Agents&rdquo;</a> (ICML 2024) &mdash; &ldquo;up to 20% higher success rate.&rdquo;
    <span class="slide-cite__sep">&middot;</span>
    Context-quality framing: <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.00615" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ACON (2025)</a> &amp; 2026 long-horizon context research.
  </p>
</div>
